I see the problem. In `seedNavGo()`:

```js
var v=inp.value.trim().replace(/^0+/,'');
if(!v)return;
```

It strips all leading zeros, so `"000"` or `"0"` becomes `""`, and then `if(!v)return;` bails out. The fix is to treat the zero case as valid.

But this is a generated file in `docs/` — the source is probably in the app itself. However, I can show you the fix. The line:

```js
var v=inp.value.trim().replace(/^0+/,'');
if(!v)return;
```

should be:

```js
var v=inp.value.trim().replace(/^0+/,'') || '0';
if(inp.value.trim()==='')return;
```

Or more simply, just change the strip to preserve at least one zero:

```js
var v=inp.value.trim().replace(/^0+(?=\d)/,'');
```

That regex `^0+(?=\d)` only strips leading zeros when there's another digit following — so `"000"` stays `"0"`, `"007"` becomes `"7"`, and `""` stays `""`.

Since this JavaScript is generated by the Gossamer build, the fix needs to go in your app source rather than in `docs/nav.js`. The regex change from `/^0+/` to `/^0+(?=\d)/` is the one-character fix — just add `(?=\d)` to the lookahead.

